orktrees allow you to check out multiple branches of the same repository into separate directories — simultaneously.(no content)Unlike cloning a repository multiple times, worktrees share a single .git directory, making them lightweight and keeping all your branches in sync.(no content)Local AI coding agents (including Claude Code, Aider, Cursor, Cline, Roo, etc.) are drastically changing both how engineers write code, and how many tasks an engineer may have in progress at a time.(no content)This can introduce unique workflow challenges that worktrees elegantly solve: when an AI agent is working on one feature, you don't want it accidentally referencing or modifying files from another feature branch.\n\n---\n\n## Practical Workflows Described in 2025–2026\n\nYou create a new branch in a worktree, spin up Claude Code or your AI agent of choice, provide instructions, and let it work on that branch.(no content)Since this is in a worktree (i.e., a different folder), you can just switch back in your editor and continue working on what you were doing, while your AI agent keeps working in the background.(no content)A git worktree is a separate working directory that shares the same repository.(no content)Same .git folder, same history, same remotes — but its own branch, its own file state, its own changes.(no content)One developer described having 5 active worktrees in a large monorepo, each with its own Claude Code instance running, working independently on different tasks.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe git worktree pattern has emerged as a best practice for running multiple AI coding agents in parallel during 2025–2026. Several open source tools have been built specifically to streamline this workflow, including **Worktrunk**, **ccswarm**, and **git-worktree-runner (gtr)**. The pattern works with agents like Claude Code, Aider, Cursor, OpenAI Codex, and others."
